#. type: Title =
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:2
#, no-wrap
msgid "Getting Started"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:8
msgid ""
"Silverblue is designed to be easy and straightforward to use, and specialist "
"knowledge should generally not be required. However, Silverblue is built "
"differently from other operating systems, and there are therefore some "
"things that it is useful to know."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:12
msgid ""
"Silverblue has different options for installing software, compared with a "
"standard Fedora Workstation (or other package-based Linux "
"distributions). These include:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:14
msgid "Flatpak apps: this is the primary way that apps get installed on Silverblue."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:15
msgid "Containers: which can be installed and used for development purposes."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:17
msgid ""
"Toolbox containers: a special kind of container that are tailored to be used "
"as a software development environment."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:22
msgid ""
"The other method of installing software on Silverblue is package layering.  "
"This is different from the other methods, and goes against the general "
"principle of immutability. Package layering adds individual packages to the "
"Silverblue system, and in so doing modifies the operating system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:26
msgid ""
"For information on link:flatpak[Flatpak] and link:package-layering[package "
"layering], see below. Information on containers can be found on the "
"link:toolbox[toolbox page]"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:28
#, no-wrap
msgid "Flatpak"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:34
msgid ""
"Flatpak is the primary way that apps can be installed on Silverblue. (For "
"information, see http://flatpak.org[flatpak.org].) Flatpak works out of the "
"box in Fedora Silverblue, and Fedora provides a small (but growing) "
"collection of apps that can be installed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:37
msgid ""
"The other main source of Flatpak apps is https://flathub.org/home[Flathub], "
"which provides a large repository of Flatpak apps that can be installed."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting up Flathub"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:44
msgid ""
"To setup Flathub on Fedora Silverblue, open the "
"https://flatpak.org/setup/Fedora/[Flathub setup page for Fedora] and click "
"the “Flathub repository file” button to download the Flathub configuration."
msgstr ""

