#. type: Title ===
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing Flatpak apps from Flathub"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:68
msgid ""
"Once the Flathub repository has been setup, it can be used to install "
"Flatpak apps. This can be done directly from the Software app, or apps can "
"be browsed on the https://flathub.org/home[Flathub website]."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:74
msgid ""
"If you choose to install apps from the Flathub website, clicking install "
"will download a file which will be opened by the Software app, which can "
"then be used to install the app. For example, to install LibreOffice, you "
"first search for and open the LibreOffice page, and then press the “Install” "
"button (1)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:78
msgid ""
"After clicking the “Install” button, a download information window will be "
"shown. Verify the correct Flatpak is being downloaded and then click on the "
"“OK” button to begin installing the LibreOffice application."
msgstr ""

#. type: Named 'title' AttributeList argument for macro 'image'
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "LibreOffice Flatpak download"
msgstr ""

#. type: Target for macro image
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "sfg_libreoffice_install.png"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:83
msgid ""
"Once the Flatpak is downloaded, the Software application will open a new "
"window with an “Install” button (1). lick this button to begin installation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:84
#, no-wrap
msgid "Flatpak command line"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:90
msgid ""
"In addition to using the Software app to install Flatpak apps, it is also "
"possible to use the `flatpak` command line interface. See the "
"http://docs.flatpak.org/en/latest/using-flatpak.html[Flatpak documentation] "
"for how to do this."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ==
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:92
#, no-wrap
msgid "Package layering"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:98
msgid ""
"Package layering works by modifying your Silverblue installation. As the "
"name implies, it works by modifying the packages from which Silverblue is "
"composed.  Any software package that is provided by Fedora can be installed "
"on Silverblue using this method."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:102
msgid ""
"A Silverblue installation with packages layered on top loses some of the "
"advantages of immutability: with layering in place, the system is no longer "
"identical to other installations, and is not as robust."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:107
msgid ""
"Nevertheless, package layering can be a useful option for installing "
"software that might not be available through other means, or for installing "
"software that, for technical reasons, needs to be part of the host operating "
"system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:110
msgid ""
"Typically, the system must be rebooted after a package has been "
"layered. This is an practical disadvantage compared with installing Flatpaks "
"or containers."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:114
msgid ""
"Package layering is generally done from the command line. However, the "
"Software application does rely on it for installing a small number of apps "
"that are currently difficult to install as Flatpaks."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:115
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing packages"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:118
msgid "Packages can be installed on Silverblue using:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:120
msgid "`$ rpm-ostree install <package name>`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:125
msgid ""
"This will download the package and any required dependencies, and recompose "
"your Silverblue image with them. `rpm-ostree` uses standard Fedora package "
"names, which can be searched using DNF (this is not available on a "
"Silverblue host, but can be used in a link:toolbox[toolbox])."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:128
msgid ""
"Once a package has been installed in this manner, it will be kept up-to-date "
"as new versions are released and as the base operating system is updated."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ===
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:129
#, no-wrap
msgid "Removing and replacing packages"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:132
msgid "A package can be removed from a Silverblue installation using:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:134
msgid "`$ rpm-ostree override remove <package name>`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:137
msgid ""
"The same `rpm-ostree override` command can be used to replace a package with "
"a different version. For example:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:139
msgid "`$ rpm-ostree override replace <path to package>`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ./pages/getting-started.adoc:142
msgid ""
"Removing and replacing packages using package layering is not generally "
"recommended. For more information, see the "
"https://rpm-ostree.readthedocs.io/en/latest/manual/administrator-handbook/[rpm-ostree "
"documentation]."
msgstr ""
